TEED Frontend Design Rules
1. Core design direction
The UI must feel clean, premium, calm, and structured.
The visual direction is inspired by Stripe-level polish, not by flashy startup clones.
Every page must prioritize clarity, spacing, hierarchy, and restraint over decoration.
Do not add visual effects unless they improve depth and focus.
Avoid noisy interfaces, crowded layouts, oversized shadows, and unnecessary gradients.
2. Brand colors
Primary brand color: #1F75FE
Accent color: #f2a705
Dark background base: #1E1E1E
Dark text color: #D4D4D4

Rules:

Use the primary blue for main actions, highlights, links, focus states, and key accents.
Use the yellow accent sparingly for emphasis only.
Do not let the yellow overpower the interface.
Do not introduce random extra brand colors.
Keep the palette disciplined and minimal.
3. Overall visual style
Use soft depth, smooth curves, and subtle layering.
Prefer rounded corners, especially rounded-2xl, rounded-[24px], or rounded-full where appropriate.
Use light shadows, never harsh shadows.
Use soft borders with low contrast.
Use blurred blob backgrounds or soft gradient glows only as supporting visuals, never as the main content.
Background effects must stay behind content and must never reduce readability.
4. Layout rules
Layout must feel spacious and balanced.
Prefer clear sections with strong separation.
Use consistent horizontal padding and vertical rhythm.
Avoid cramped designs.
Use max width containers such as max-w-6xl, max-w-7xl, max-w-xl, etc depending on the section.
Prefer grid and flex layouts that scale cleanly across screen sizes.
Mobile-first design is mandatory.
Desktop layouts should feel elegant, not stretched or empty.
5. Typography rules
Typography must be clean and restrained.
Headings should feel confident and compact, not oversized for no reason.
Body text should be highly readable and never too light or too small.
Maintain clear hierarchy:
large heading
supporting subheading
body text
labels and helper text
Avoid decorative fonts.
Use font weight and spacing for hierarchy instead of random color changes.
6. Button rules
Buttons must feel Stripe-inspired: compact, smooth, premium, and controlled.
Primary buttons use the brand blue.
Secondary buttons use neutral surfaces with subtle borders.
Accent buttons use yellow only when emphasis is truly needed.
Use rounded-full or soft rounded buttons consistently.
Hover states must be subtle:
slight shadow increase
slight lift
no dramatic scale jumps
Disabled states must be obvious but still clean.
Do not use giant gradients, neon glows, or over-animated buttons.
7. Input and form rules
Inputs must feel soft, modern, and easy to scan.
Use rounded corners and subtle borders.
Use clear labels above inputs.
Error states must be clean and visible, never aggressive.
Focus states must use soft blue glow/ring based on #1F75FE.
Forms must have strong spacing between fields.
Avoid clutter around inputs.
Form sections should often live inside soft cards or clean containers.
8. Card rules
Cards must feel elevated but not heavy.
Use soft shadows and low-contrast borders.
Prefer large rounded corners.
Card content must have generous padding.
Cards should separate information clearly.
Do not stack too many nested cards unless absolutely needed.
Cards must not look like Bootstrap leftovers.
9. Motion and animation rules
Motion must be smooth, subtle, and purposeful.
Use animation to support hierarchy, focus, and premium feel.
Good motion examples:
soft fade-in
slight upward entrance
slow blob drifting
subtle hover lift
gentle opacity transitions
Bad motion examples:
bouncing
spinning panels
exaggerated scaling
flashy hero gimmicks
Motion should never distract from content.
Prefer transition-all duration-200 or duration-300 for standard interactions.
Use Framer Motion only where it adds real polish.
10. Blob and background effect rules
Blob visuals should be soft, abstract, blurred, and low-opacity.
Use blob effects mainly in hero sections, auth pages, onboarding pages, and premium highlights.
Prefer CSS gradients, blurred circles, layered glow shapes, or SVG blobs before using heavy libraries.
Blob effects must not dominate the page.
Keep them ambient, not loud.
Avoid sharp-edged random shapes pretending to be blobs.
11. Stripe-like style rules

To match the Stripe feel:

prioritize whitespace
use strong but minimal hierarchy
keep sections clean
use soft gradients and blur carefully
make CTAs feel intentional
maintain visual precision
use restrained premium styling instead of overdesign

Do not:

overuse glassmorphism
add too many colors
add unnecessary icons everywhere
use loud shadows
force futuristic effects
make everything look like a crypto landing page
12. Dark mode rules
Dark mode must feel deliberate, not inverted lazily.
Use #1E1E1E as a main dark surface reference.
Text in dark mode should be readable and calm, such as #D4D4D4.
Borders should stay subtle, not bright gray.
Shadows in dark mode should remain soft.
Primary blue and accent yellow should still work cleanly in dark mode.
Do not let dark mode become muddy or overly blue-tinted.
13. Component consistency rules
Reuse global UI components whenever possible.
Use shared:
Button
Input
Card
Section wrapper
Form layout patterns
Do not reinvent component styles in each page.
All components must follow the same radius, spacing, shadow, and transition language.
Avoid one-off styling unless absolutely necessary.
14. Spacing rules
Spacing must feel intentional and consistent.
Prefer generous spacing between sections and components.
Keep internal card padding consistent.
Avoid random margin values unless there is a real reason.
Visual rhythm matters as much as color.
15. Code style rules for frontend
Use React functional components.
Use Tailwind utility classes cleanly and consistently.
Keep JSX readable and structured.
Extract reusable UI pieces instead of repeating large style blocks.
Prefer maintainable code over clever hacks.
Do not inline giant style messes unless unavoidable.
Respect existing project structure and naming.
16. What Copilot must avoid
Do not generate generic Bootstrap-looking UI
Do not generate cluttered enterprise dashboard styling
Do not use too many colors
Do not use harsh borders
Do not use strong glassmorphism everywhere
Do not use random gradients on every section
Do not use exaggerated animation
Do not make components inconsistent with the global design system
Do not create visual noise
17. What Copilot should optimize for
premium simplicity
visual restraint
consistency
reusable components
responsive balance
elegant hierarchy
clean dark mode
subtle motion
Stripe-inspired polish without copying Stripe blindly